 Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"en":{"about 1140–about 1178":"about 1140–about 1178","1140–1178":"1140–1178","1141–Male":"1141–Deceased","1140–1204":"1140–1204","1165–1217":"1165–1217","1172–1217":"1172–1217","1114–1175":"1114–1175","–Female":"Deceased","about 1172":"about 1172","about 1140":"about 1140","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1141":"1141","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","1217":"1217","1204":"1204","1114":"1114","1178":"1178","before 1141":"before 1141","before 1172":"before 1172","about 1178":"about 1178","Aft 1175":"after about 1175","about 1165":"about 1165","Kilkhampton Manor, Stowe, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Middleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places so called. In over thirty instances from many different areas, the name is from Old English <i>midel</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. However, Middleton on the Hill near Leominster in Herefordshire appears in Domesday Book as <i>Miceltune</i>, the first element clearly being Old English <i>micel</i> ‘large’, ‘great’ (see   Middlebrook  ). Middleton Baggot and Middleton Priors in Shropshire have early spellings that suggest <i>gem̄thhyll</i> (from <i>gem̄th</i> ‘confluence’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’) + <i>tūn</i> as the origin. This surname is also found in Scotland and Ireland.","History: A Scottish family of this name derives it from lands at Middleto(u)n near Kincardine. The Scottish physician Peter Middleton practiced in New York City after 1752 and was one of the founders of the medical school at King's College (now Columbia University) in 1767. One of the earliest of the Charleston, SC, Middleton family of prominent legislators was Arthur Middleton, born in Charleston in 1681. The name has also been established in Ireland since at least the 13th century; its presence was reinforced by settlers in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Midthun","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of about ten farmsteads in western Norway named Midtun, from Old Norse <i>mith</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tún</i> ‘enclosure, farmstead’. Compare   Middleton  ."]},{"name":"Melton","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from any of various places, for example in Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire, all of which have the same origin as   Middleton  , with Old English <i>middel</i> replaced by its Old Norse equivalent <i>methal</i> after the Scandinavian settlement of northern and eastern England."]},{"name":"Middlebrook","meanings":["English: habitational name from a lost <i>Micklebrook</i> in Blackburn (Lancashire), recorded as <i>Mikelbroc</i> in the 13th century. The placename appears to derive from Old English <i>micel</i> ‘big’ + <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’. The surname has undergone a dissimilatory or folk-etymological change from <i>Mickle-</i> to <i>Middle-</i>."]},{"name":"Milton","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the many places called Milton, or sometimes Middleton (see   Middleton  ) and occasionally Melton (see   Melton  ), most of which derive from Old English <i>middel</i> ‘middle’ or <i>myln</i> ‘mill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]}]},{"name":"Adeline","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["diminutive of <i>Adèle</i> (  see  Adele  ), used occasionally in England from the early 16th century onwards, and now also found in the wider English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Baroness Adeline Gundrada de Middleton was born about 1140, in Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England as the daughter of Nicholas de Middleton I and Mrs Nicholas de Middleton I. She married Sir Richard de Grenville III before 1172, in Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died about 1178, in Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40."},"et":{"about 1140–about 1178":"umbes 1140–umbes 1178","1140–1178":"1140–1178","1141–Male":"1141–Surnud","1140–1204":"1140–1204","1165–1217":"1165–1217","1172–1217":"1172–1217","1114–1175":"1114–1175","–Female":"Surnud","about 1172":"umbes 1172","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1141":"1141","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","1217":"1217","1204":"1204","1114":"1114","1178":"1178","before 1141":"enne 1141","before 1172":"enne 1172","about 1178":"umbes 1178","Aft 1175":"umbes pärast 1175","about 1165":"umbes 1165","Kilkhampton Manor, Stowe, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"about 1140–about 1178":"noin 1140–noin 1178","1140–1178":"1140–1178","1141–Male":"1141–Kuollut","1140–1204":"1140–1204","1165–1217":"1165–1217","1172–1217":"1172–1217","1114–1175":"1114–1175","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1172":"noin 1172","abo